---
import ClerriLayout from '../../layouts/ClerriLayout.astro';
---
<ClerriLayout title="Patient Directory" section="directory">

<div class="page-head">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">08 · Consumer Acquisition</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">The single <em>highest-ROI</em> competitive move.</h1>
  <p class="page-sub">This concept is a high-priority strategic initiative. Research validates it: practice density is a marketing weapon competitors can't replicate, and BoomCloud's "Patient Marketplace" — the supposed moat — is a paper tiger.</p>
</div>

<div class="page-body">

  <div class="takeaway">
    <span class="tk-lbl">Bottom line</span>
    <p>Practice density is the one competitive weapon nobody can copy. A patient-facing directory turns 5,000 practices into a demand magnet — and BoomCloud's version is a gated lead form, not a directory. This is the highest-ROI bet on the board.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="progress-track"><div class="progress-fill" data-progress-fill="directory"></div></div>
  <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--muted)">Progress: <span data-progress-here="directory">0 / 0</span></p>

  <div class="callout zest-hi">
    <div class="lbl">The Asymmetry</div>
    <p>Clerri has <strong>5,000+ practices</strong>. BoomCloud's ThePatientMarketplace.com gets <strong>2,400 visits/month with 79.6% bounce rate</strong>, propped up by paid display ads. The "national patient directory" narrative is being claimed without the asset. Clerri's structural scale + modest investment dwarfs them within 6 months and neutralizes BoomCloud's only true differentiator.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="callout mint">
    <div class="lbl">The hidden differentiator nobody's talking about</div>
    <p>The <strong>patient-to-practice referral mechanism</strong> ("Don't see your dentist? Refer them") is the differentiator most competitive analysis is missing. It's structurally unique:</p>
    <ul style="font-size:0.95rem;padding-left:1.25rem;margin:0.5rem 0;line-height:1.65">
      <li><strong>vs. BoomCloud</strong> — they're practice-side. No mechanism for a patient to bring their own dentist on. Adding it would require building the patient-side they don't have.</li>
      <li><strong>vs. dental savings plans</strong> (DentalPlans.com, Aetna, Careington) — closed networks. You use <em>their</em> dentists. You can't bring yours.</li>
      <li><strong>vs. Zocdoc-style directories</strong> — they list existing accepting-doctors. They don't onboard new ones from patient requests.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="margin-top:0.5rem">Clerri's referral mechanism is a clean two-sided platform flywheel: <strong>patient demand → practice acquisition → directory expansion → more patient utility</strong>. Each patient request becomes a warm BD lead with patient context attached (the strongest possible practice-side opener — see <a href="/clerri/competitors" style="color:var(--zest);font-weight:600">Competitor Intel</a>).</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.5rem"><strong>AEO + thought-leadership angle (high-value content opportunity):</strong> this is exactly the kind of mechanism LLMs (ChatGPT, Perplexity, Claude) explain when asked "what makes Clerri different from BoomCloud / DentalPlans / Zocdoc?" If we publish content that answers that question directly with this mechanism, we own the citation. A "How Clerri brings new dental practices onto the platform" canonical piece + "Why patient-led practice acquisition works" thought piece both qualify.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.5rem"><strong>The story worth telling loudly:</strong> if the referral funnel hits a measurable success rate (target: 50-65% practice onboarding from patient referrals vs. 11% from cold outreach), <em>that's</em> the headline number to put on the homepage, in earned media pitches, and in DSO sales decks. Track from Day 1.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Strategic rationale</h2>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Why this matters</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Captures bottom-of-funnel patient demand (72M+ uninsured)</li>
        <li>Direct revenue: every enrollment is recurring (Bucket 02)</li>
        <li>Defensible: practice density makes directory genuinely useful</li>
        <li>Practice value: tangible patient acquisition no competitor offers</li>
        <li>Category narrative: positions Clerri as connector</li>
        <li>Two-tier monetization: free baseline, paid premium</li>
        <li>Designed for horizontal expansion (DPC, vision, med spa)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Build components</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Geographic search + plan filtering + practice profiles</li>
        <li>Base practice listings (location, contact, plans, reviews)</li>
        <li>Premium tier (featured placement, lead capture, analytics)</li>
        <li>Local SEO foundation (city-level pages at scale via AI)</li>
        <li>PMS integration for live availability</li>
        <li>Sunbit financing integration on listing pages</li>
        <li>Compliance review (DMPO, state-specific)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Phased rollout hypothesis</h2>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card" style="border-color:var(--clerri-green)">
      <div class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--clerri-green);letter-spacing:0.1em">PHASE 1 · MONTHS 1-3</div>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Validate</h3>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Scope with product/eng</li>
        <li>Decide build vs partner (NexHealth integration could accelerate)</li>
        <li>BoomCloud Marketplace teardown — what works, what doesn't</li>
        <li>Compliance pre-clearance (DMPO, state-specific)</li>
        <li>Pilot landing page in 5 metros to measure demand</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--clerri-green);letter-spacing:0.1em">PHASE 2 · MONTHS 4-6</div>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Build MVP</h3>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Practice profiles + basic search</li>
        <li>Free tier across all practices (default-on)</li>
        <li>City-page SEO scaffolding via AI (workflow C)</li>
        <li>Soft launch in 3-5 metros with paid geo support</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--clerri-green);letter-spacing:0.1em">PHASE 3 · MONTHS 7-9</div>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Monetize</h3>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Premium tier features (featured placement, lead capture, analytics)</li>
        <li>Sunbit financing integration on practice pages</li>
        <li>Lead routing economics analysis</li>
        <li>Practice success measurement framework</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card" style="border-color:var(--clerri-green)">
      <div class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--clerri-green);letter-spacing:0.1em">PHASE 4 · MONTHS 10-12+</div>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0">Scale</h3>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Scale local SEO across all 5,000+ practice locations</li>
        <li>Paid acquisition where unit economics work</li>
        <li>Integrate employer channel (ICHRA + LSA reimbursement)</li>
        <li>Open architecture for adjacent specialties (horizontal thesis)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ===== RESEARCH VALIDATION ===== -->
  <h2>Why browse-first wins <em>(the research backing)</em></h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:65ch">Every category-leading healthcare and local-services directory has won with a browse-first model. The lead-broker model (form-gated, BoomCloud-style) has never produced a category leader in healthcare. The data:</p>

  <h3>Category-analog wins</h3>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>Browse-first winner</th><th>Lead-broker losers</th><th>Outcome</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Medical appointments</td><td><strong>Zocdoc</strong> ($1.2B valuation)</td><td>DocFinder + others</td><td>Lead-brokers gone, Zocdoc category default</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Restaurant reservations</td><td><strong>OpenTable</strong></td><td>Phone-call brokers</td><td>Browse-first won outright</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Doctor reviews/search</td><td><strong>Healthgrades / Vitals</strong></td><td>Old lead-gen sites</td><td>Browse-first owns category</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Home rental</td><td><strong>Airbnb</strong></td><td>Vacation rental brokers</td><td>Browse-first won</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Local services</td><td><strong>Yelp</strong> (consumer brand)</td><td>HomeAdvisor / Angi</td><td>Yelp owns consumer brand; HomeAdvisor monetizes but never matched trust</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>DPC doctors (Clerri's vertical analog)</strong></td><td><strong>Hint Health</strong> — 2,700+ public listings, no form gate</td><td>—</td><td>Hint defined the category</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Industry data backing browse-first</h3>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Consumer behavior (BrightLocal 2024)</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li><strong>81%</strong> of consumers research a business online before contacting</li>
        <li><strong>76%</strong> visit a website before contacting a business</li>
        <li><strong>84%</strong> trust online reviews as much as personal recommendations</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Form abandonment in healthcare lead-gen</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li><strong>65-85% abandonment</strong> in healthcare lead-capture forms (HubSpot 2024)</li>
        <li>BoomCloud's <strong>79.6% bounce</strong> sits squarely in this range — that's not a bug, that's the model's ceiling</li>
        <li>Lead quality from gated forms = lower LTV than self-chosen patients (2-3× difference in healthcare consumer research)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>SEO compound math</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Mature Yelp listing pages generate <strong>~30 organic visits/month each</strong></li>
        <li>5,000 Clerri practice profiles × 30 = <strong>~150,000 monthly organic visits</strong> with zero paid spend</li>
        <li>BoomCloud spends paid ads to get 2,400 visits/month</li>
        <li>Compounds for 12-18 months as SEO ramps; defensible long-term</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>The strategic pattern</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Browse-first models built the consumer brands in healthcare</li>
        <li>Lead-brokers monetize but never produce category leaders</li>
        <li>PE exits reward defensible consumer brand assets, not lead-gen pages</li>
        <li>Clerri's position (5K+ practices, Charlesbank, multi-year horizon) aligns with the winning model</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Pitch-ready facts (use straight or paraphrase)</h3>
  <div class="callout">
    <ol style="margin:0;padding-left:1.25rem;font-size:0.95rem;line-height:1.7">
      <li><strong>"Every category-leading healthcare directory has won with browse-first: Zocdoc, Healthgrades, OpenTable, Hint Health. The lead-broker model has never produced a category leader in healthcare."</strong></li>
      <li><strong>"BoomCloud's gated Patient Marketplace has a 79.6% bounce rate. That's the structural ceiling of form-gated lead-gen, confirmed by HubSpot 2024 data showing 65-85% abandonment across healthcare lead forms."</strong></li>
      <li><strong>"At 5,000 practices × ~30 organic visits/profile/month at maturity = 150,000 monthly organic visits with zero paid spend. BoomCloud pays for ads to get 2,400."</strong></li>
      <li><strong>"PE exit valuations reward defensible consumer brand assets. A real directory + 5K SEO-indexed profile pages is a moat. A lead-capture form is replaceable in a quarter."</strong></li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <!-- ===== LISTING MECHANICS ===== -->
  <h2>How listings would work <em>(the business model)</em></h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:65ch">The model has to (a) maximize patient utility — every member practice listed — while (b) creating room for incremental revenue, (c) staying clear of dark patterns, and (d) clearing compliance. Here's the proposed structure.</p>

  <h3>Consent model</h3>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Existing Clerri practices — opt-in by default</h4>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">All 5,000+ member practices automatically listed in free tier at directory launch. Notice sent 30 days pre-launch with opt-out instructions. Directory listing becomes part of being a Clerri customer (opt-out preserved as practice agency).</p>
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--muted);font-style:italic;margin-top:0.5rem">Why opt-in-default: network effects only work if listings are dense. Cold launch with empty geos = patient-side trust crash.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>New practices — contract-level consent</h4>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">Directory listing built into new-customer MSA from day one. Practices know what they're signing up for. Premium tier upgrade offered during onboarding.</p>
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--muted);font-style:italic;margin-top:0.5rem">Patient-facing fields (hours, accepting new patients) come with accuracy obligations in the MSA — stale data degrades the directory.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>What practices control</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Profile content (description, photos, story)</li>
        <li>Public hours + new-patient acceptance status</li>
        <li>Plan tier visibility</li>
        <li>Whether reviews are accepted</li>
        <li>Opt-out of listing entirely (with written notice)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>What Clerri controls</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Default listing format + design</li>
        <li>Default sort order (distance + rating)</li>
        <li>Featured slot rotation algorithm</li>
        <li>Search filter logic</li>
        <li>Practice profile URL structure</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Three-tier model</h3>
  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="card" style="border-color:var(--clerri-green);background:var(--cotton-plus)">
      <span class="pill pill-zest">Tier 1 · DEFAULT</span>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0;color:var(--clerri-green)">Free</h3>
      <p style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-size:1.65rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--clerri-green);margin:0.5rem 0;line-height:1">$0 / month</p>
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--ink-soft);margin:0 0 0.75rem">All Clerri practices automatically</p>
      <ul style="font-size:0.85rem;padding-left:1rem;margin:0">
        <li>Standard profile page</li>
        <li>Listed in search (sorted by distance + rating)</li>
        <li>Plan pricing + benefits shown</li>
        <li>Hours, languages, specialty tags</li>
        <li>Patient reviews (opt-in)</li>
        <li>Contact info + "Join membership" CTA</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <span class="pill pill-zest">Tier 2 · PAID</span>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0;color:var(--clerri-green)">Premium</h3>
      <p style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-size:1.65rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--clerri-green);margin:0.5rem 0;line-height:1">$99-149 / month</p>
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--ink-soft);margin:0 0 0.75rem">Practice opt-in upgrade</p>
      <ul style="font-size:0.85rem;padding-left:1rem;margin:0">
        <li><strong>Featured slot</strong> in their geo (rotating)</li>
        <li>Photo gallery (interior, team, results)</li>
        <li>Lead capture form on profile</li>
        <li>Analytics dashboard (views, calls, clicks)</li>
        <li>Priority support</li>
        <li>Premium badge on listing card</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <span class="pill pill-zest">Tier 3 · DSO</span>
      <h3 style="margin:0.5rem 0;color:var(--clerri-green)">Enterprise</h3>
      <p style="font-family:'Fraunces',serif;font-size:1.65rem;font-weight:700;color:var(--clerri-green);margin:0.5rem 0;line-height:1">Custom</p>
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--ink-soft);margin:0 0 0.75rem">For DSOs / multi-location</p>
      <ul style="font-size:0.85rem;padding-left:1rem;margin:0">
        <li>Unified DSO brand across all locations</li>
        <li>Aggregated DSO-level analytics</li>
        <li>Custom landing pages per location</li>
        <li>Co-branded patient experience</li>
        <li>Dedicated CSM relationship</li>
        <li>Priority placement across markets</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Why NOT bidding or pay-per-lead</h3>
  <div class="callout wine">
    <div class="lbl">The dark patterns we explicitly avoid</div>
    <p>Bidding / pay-per-lead / pay-to-rank schemes look attractive — they're how HomeAdvisor monetizes. But they're <strong>structurally what BoomCloud is doing</strong>. They erode patient trust, create perverse incentives (highest-paying practice gets the patient, not best-fit), and trap Clerri in the lead-broker positioning that the competitive narrative is built against.</p>
    <p style="margin-top:0.5rem"><strong>Flat-fee tiers preserve patient trust + give practices predictable economics + create an upgrade path without the dark-pattern overhead.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <h3>How Premium ranking actually works (no dark patterns)</h3>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>The rules</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li><strong>Default sort = distance + rating</strong>, not premium status</li>
        <li><strong>One featured slot per search results page</strong>, rotating among premium subscribers in that geo</li>
        <li>Premium gets a visible "Featured" badge — patients can see the distinction</li>
        <li>Search filters always honored (filter "open weekends" → premium-but-closed practices are excluded)</li>
        <li>Patients can always re-sort or filter premium-only off</li>
        <li>No buy-the-top-of-results scheme</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>What this preserves</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.9rem;padding-left:1rem">
        <li>Patient trust (no pay-to-win deception)</li>
        <li>Best-fit matching by default</li>
        <li>Practices know what they're getting (rotating slot, not algorithmic gaming)</li>
        <li>Revenue without compromising consumer product</li>
        <li>Clean compliance story for DMPO + state advertising rules</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Revenue math (illustrative)</h3>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="lbl">At maturity (month 18-24)</div>
    <ul style="font-size:0.95rem;padding-left:1.25rem;line-height:1.7;margin:0.5rem 0">
      <li><strong>5,000 free-tier listings</strong> — $0 directly, full patient utility, full SEO compounding</li>
      <li><strong>500 premium upgrades</strong> (10% of base) × $99/mo = <strong>~$594K ARR</strong></li>
      <li><strong>20 DSO enterprise deals</strong> × $5K/mo average = <strong>~$1.2M ARR</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Total directory ARR at maturity ~$1.8M</strong> — additive to core membership revenue</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-size:0.875rem;opacity:0.85;margin-top:0.75rem;font-style:italic">Directory's main strategic value isn't this revenue — it's defensible consumer brand + practice retention + patient acquisition into core membership. The $1.8M is a nice secondary outcome.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Compliance considerations</h3>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>DMPO + state regulation</h4>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">Dental membership plan organization rules vary by state. Some states (CA, NY) have specific advertising disclosures required. Compliance pre-clearance is Phase 1 work, not Phase 4.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Patient referral incentive rules</h4>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">Most states prohibit pay-for-referral in healthcare. Our model avoids this: practices pay for <strong>visibility + features</strong>, not per-patient-acquired. Clean legal footing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Accuracy obligations</h4>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">Practices must keep listings accurate (hours, accepting new patients, pricing). Built into MSA. Stale data trust crash is a real risk — requires real-time PMS sync infrastructure.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Reviews + ratings policy</h4>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem">Patient reviews — opt-in per practice. Clerri moderates for spam/fraud. Practices can flag inappropriate reviews; cannot delete legitimate negative ones (Yelp precedent).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Tasks</h2>
  <div data-section="directory">
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-01-teardown" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Personally teardown BoomCloud's ThePatientMarketplace — document everything</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-02-product-scope" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Phase 1: scoping meeting with product + eng — build vs partner decision</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-03-nexhealth" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Evaluate NexHealth (400+ integrations) as build-acceleration partner</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-04-compliance" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Compliance pre-clearance — DMPO + state-specific for consumer-facing directory</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-05-pilot-metros" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Pilot landing page in 5 high-density Clerri metros to measure consumer demand</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-06-jim-greenlight" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Greenlight conversation with leadership — present economic model + phased commit</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-07-tier-pricing" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Validate $99-149 premium tier pricing with 10-15 customer interviews</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-08-consent-msa" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Draft directory consent + MSA language with legal team (existing + new customers)</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-09-rotation-algorithm" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Design premium featured-slot rotation algorithm (equal time, no pay-to-rank)</div></div></label>
    <label class="task"><input type="checkbox" data-track="dir-10-reviews-policy" data-section="directory" /><div class="task-content"><div class="task-title">Reviews + ratings policy + moderation framework</div></div></label>
  </div>

  <div class="note-block">
    <div class="note-label">Directory strategy notes <span class="note-saved">✓ saved</span></div>
    <textarea data-note="directory-notes" placeholder="Build vs partner decision rationale, pilot results, compliance constraints, partner conversations..."></textarea>
  </div>

  <div class="topic-foot">
    <a href="/clerri/aeo-seo"><span class="dir">← Prev</span><span class="name">07 · AEO / SEO / SEM</span></a>
    <a href="/clerri/ai-stack"><span class="dir">Next →</span><span class="name">09 · AI Marketing Stack</span></a>
  </div>

</div>
</ClerriLayout>
